descript.abstract: This point feature class represents the center (not the true centroid) of each tax parcel polygon. The site address information is associated with each point that has a site address. Every point has a PIN (Parcel Identification Number) value. If there are multiple PINS associated with a particular tax parcel, the points are stacked on top of each other. The points were created by a process that located the approximate center from the polygon feature class.
descript.purpose: This feature class is used as the reference data for two geocoding services, one that can geocode to the PIN number, and one that can geocode to the site address. This feature class is generally not recommended for cartographic purposes.
descript.supplinf: The original process used to create this file located the centroid of each parcel. However, the mathematical centroid can fall outside of a polygon's boundary. Therefore, a different process was used that would ensure the point would be located inside the polygon boundary. This process did produce some unexpected results, as the center of some parcels is not always located where a person might assume the center should be.

procstep.procdesc: The TaxParcel coverage was copied locally, and the ParcelAttribute table was exported from ArcSDE into a .DBF.

The Feature to Point tool in ArcGIS Toolbox was used to create a point inside of each polygon (the INSIDE option was used). The Add XY Coordinates tool was used to add XY values to each of the points.

The ParcelAttribute .DBF file and the TaxParcel shapefile were joined on LowPIN and PIN, respectively. An X and Y attribute were added to the ParcelAttribute table. All records containing an X value in the TaxParcel shapefile were selected. The X and Y values were calculated with the values from the joined shapefile. The join was removed.
The selected records were exported to a .DBF.
The .DBF was converted to an INFO file using ArcINFO Workstation.
The site addresses in the INFO file were parsed using the ADDRESSPARSE command. The parsed address information was pulled from the file using the PULLITEMS command.
The INFO file was exported to a .DBF.
Using the Add XY Data command in ArcMap, the exported .DBF file was mapped, and the results exported to a shapefile.
The parsed street names in the shapefile were manually reviewed, and obvious mistakes were corrected (e.g., "FOURTEENMILE" was changed to "FOURTEEN MILE").
The shapefile was imported into a personal geodatabase.
Extra attributes were dropped from the feature class, and the parsed address field were renamed to meet Oakland County standards.
